17 SECTION 5.(a) G.S. 15A-974 reads as rewritten:
18 "§ 15A-974. Exclusion or suppression of unlawfully obtained evidence.
19 (a) Upon timely motion, evidence must be suppressed if:
20 (1) Its exclusion is required by the Constitution of the United States or the
21 Constitution of the State of North Carolina; or
22 (2) It is obtained as a result of a substantial violation of the provisions of this
23 Chapter. In determining whether a violation is substantial, the court must
24 consider all the circumstances, including:
25 a. The importance of the particular interest violated;
26 b. The extent of the deviation from lawful conduct;
27 c. The extent to which the violation was willful;
28 d. The extent to which exclusion will tend to deter future violations of
29 this Chapter.
30 Evidence shall not be suppressed under this subdivision if the person
31 committing the violation of the provision or provisions under this Chapter
32 acted under the objectively reasonable, good faith belief that the actions were
33 lawful.
34 (a1) If evidence was obtained as the result of a search that was supported by probable
35 cause at the time of the search, no evidence obtained as a result of that search shall be suppressed
36 solely on the basis of either of the following:
37 (1) A subsequent determination that a substance believed to be a controlled
38 substance at the time of the search was not a controlled substance.
39 (2) A subsequent determination that the presence of a controlled substance at the
40 time of the search was not a violation of law.
41 (b) The court, in making a determination whether or not evidence shall be suppressed
42 under this section, shall make findings of fact and conclusions of law which shall be included in
43 the record, pursuant to G.S. 15A-977(f)."
44 SECTION 5.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2023, and applies to
45 motions filed on or after that date.
